    {
      "note_no": "141",
      "note": "Explaining this injunction, expressed in the second person plural, Ibn Kathir points out that it is addressed to all believers, and that it refers to their behaviour towards everyone, be he believer or unbeliever; in this he obviously relies on the interpretation advanced by Ibn 'Abbas (and quoted by Razi): \"It means, 'Be humble before God and do not behave with false pride towards anyone'.\" According to some later commentators (e.g., Tabari, Zamakhshari, Baghawi, Razi), the meaning is wider, namely, \"do not overstep the bounds of what God has ordained\", or \"do not exceed the limits of equity\"."
